did.abstract: This collection consists of material gathered and created by the George Washington University Progressive Student Union as a function of their advocacy and campaign work. The type of material in the collection includes flyers, newsletters, correspondence, meeting agendas, newspaper articles, brochures, educational material, campaign material, and organizational records. This material dates from 1966 to 2008 with the majority of the material falling within the dates 1988-1996. Topics addressed in this collection include anti-apartheid, education reform, economics, environmentalism, feminism, human rights, international relations, labor union, LGBTQ issues, poverty, racism, sexism, and workers rights.
did.physloc: Materials may be stored off-site, and may require additional retrieval time. Please contact the Special Collections Research Center for more information.

archdesc.bioghist:
Biographical/Historical note The Progressive Student Union (PSU) is a student organization at The George Washington University. The PSU was established in the 1980s as a multi-issue, social peace and justice student organization working to combat all forms of oppression. The PSU served as a coalition-building group, a direct action group, a campaign planning group, an event sponsor, and a provider of solidarity.
The organization worked on a broad spectrum of social justice issues (including but not limited to racism, sexism, classism, heterosexism, ableism, homelessness, poverty, US foreign and domestic policy, environmental destruction, corporate control of the media, corporate control of educational institutions, increasing corporate power globally, exploitative labor policies, union busting, animal exploitation, censorship, free trade agreements, violence, war, and corporate globalization) with a variety of campus, community, national, and international organizations. The PSU was active in national and local movements, beginning with anti-apartheid/disinvestment campaigns in the 1980s. In the 1980s, it operated as the east coast headquarters of the Progressive Student Network (PSN), and for several years published the PSN News, the periodical newspaper of the Progressive Student Network. After the PSN declined after 1994, the PSU continued to operate as a catch-all progressive group, organizing and advocating for scores of issues, including women's reproductive rights, the power of labor unions, Native American rights, environmental sustainability, and many others.
In recent years, PSU worked to end GW's contract with the Coca-Cola Company, to increase the wages and benefits of security guards in non-academic buildings and food service workers in the J Street restaurant complex, and to support the Employee Free Choice Act. The PSU was also instrumental in establishing the Socially Responsible Initiatives Commission in 2007-2008, which helps distribute resources by students designated for events or campaigns that promote social responsibility. The PSU worked and works with both local organizations such as DC Student Labor Action Project and local unions, as well as national organizations like United Students Against Sweatshops and Jobs With Justice. The Progressive Student Union is non-hierarchical organization with no elected officials; the group seeks to make decisions by consensus and operates through volunteers. (Source: Progressive Student Union website, , 2006.)

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content note
scopecontent.p: This collection contains flyers, correspondence, meeting agendas, attendance lists, contact information, newspapers, newsletters, magazines, clippings, brochures, organization policy statements, photographs, financial records, petitions, notes, event plans, essays, GW forms and reports, educational material, organizational records, solicitation letters, campaign material, material from conferences, stickers, political campaign memorabilia, and fact sheets. The material dates from 1966 to 2008, with the bulk of the material dating from 1988 to 1996. These are the records of the Progression Student Union of George Washington University. This collection reflects the activities and beliefs of this organization. Topics addresses in this material include anti-apartheid, education reform, economics, environmentalism, feminism, human rights, international relations, LGBTQ issues, poverty, racism, sexism, and workers rights. These records were donated to the University Archives by a student leader of the Progressive Student Union in 2009.

The records are divided into five series: Operational Documents, Campaigns, Organizations, Periodicals, and Memorabilia. Upon donation, the contents of folders in this collection often did not correspond to the folder label. During formal archival processing duplicates were removed, and materials were moved into appropriate folders when neccessary.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research. Some records in Series 1 and 2 are restricted for 75 years from date of record creation.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: Organized into five series: Operational Documents, Campaigns, Organizations, Periodicals, and Memorabilia. The Campaigns series is organized into eleven subseries: Education/Student Issues, Environment, Foreign Countries, Human/Animal Rights, International Relations/Trade, Labor, LGBTQ Issues, Racism, War and Peace, Women's Issues, and Other Campaigns/Issues.
Where possible, series and subseries are arranged alphabetically or chronologically.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation note
prefercite.p: Please cite unpublished materials in the following way:
Please provide the title and date of item, catalog number (if applicable it will be found written on the folder), name of the collection, name of the repository, and location of the repository.

Example: Allison Robbins to President Stephen Trachtenberg, 29 July 2002, RG0134 Series 1, Box 3, Folder 4. Progressive Student Union records, University Archives, Special Collections Research Center, The George Washington University, Washington, D.C.

scopecontent.head: Operational Documents
scopecontent.p: The materials of this series include photographs, event flyers, information flyers, correspondence, financial records, meeting agendas, meeting attendance and contact lists, organization policies and guidelines, forms from the university, records from publications, information packets, images used on flyers, newspaper clipping, stationary, and merchandise catalogs. The material dates from 1987 to 2003, but it is predominately from 1990 to 1996. The material in this series was predominantly created by the GW Progression Student Union and relates to how they operated. It reveals individuals who were involved in this student organization and the types of activities undertaken. Rusty Stahl and Allison Robbins are two of the students whose names appear often in these records. Some letters from GW President Stephen J. Trachtenberg are within this series. Records relating to the Progressive Student Union publications, Unfiltered and Buff and Blue, are also within this series.

arrangement.head: Operational Documents
arrangement.p: The Operational Documents folders are grouped by type but are not organized into subseries. The folders generally follow this order: photos, flyers, publicity documents, correspondence, finances, agendas, contact information, and other.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Some records in this series are closed for 75 years from date of record creation.

scopecontent.head: Campaigns
scopecontent.p: The materials of this series include event flyers, information flyers, newspaper and magazine articles, petitions, correspondences, notes, event plans, essays, background material, letters from GW officials, published GW documents, newsletters, and brochures. The material dates from 1966 to 2008, but it is predominately from 1989 to 1996. This series reflects the political and social issues that were important to the Progressive Student Union and the actions that they took in regards to these issues. Much of the material in this series related to campaigns that the Progressive Student Union was involved with at George Washington University, including recycling/green initiatives, labor disputes with cafeteria and parking staff, initiatives against sweatshop labor, work against particular industries connected to education, and demands for financial aid. Some campaigns were Washington, D.C. specific, such as community service work or anti-World Bank protests. Other campaigns were national or international in scope, including demilitarization, gay-rights, pro-choice, pro-Native American, anti-apartheid, anti-Gulf War, and pro-environment advocacy.

This series is divided into eleven subseries based on content which are arranged in alphabetical order. The subseries are: Education/Student Issues, Environment, Foreign Countries, Human/Animal Rights, International Relations/Trade, Labor, LGBTQ Issues, Racism, War and Peace, Women's Issues, and Other Campaigns/Issues.

arrangement.head: Campaigns
arrangement.p: The Campaigns series is organized into eleven subseries: Education/Student Issues, Environment, Foreign Countries, Human/Animal Rights, International Relations/Trade, Labor, LGBTQ Issues, Racism, War and Peace, Women's Issues, and Other Campaigns/Issues. Within some of the subseries, files are organized alphabetically by title.

scopecontent.head: Organizations
scopecontent.p: The materials of this series include brochures, educational material, event flyers, information flyers, organizational records, correspondence, solicitation letters, articles, newsletters, campaign material, contact information, material from conferences, and fact sheets. The material dates from 1970 to 2003, but it is predominately from 1990 to 1996. This series contains items created by various international, national, regional, city, and student organizations whose beliefs and/or agendas were favored by the GW Progressive Student Union. Students from the Progressive Student Union worked with some of these organizations; Rusty Stahl was a leader in multiple student organizations for example. In other cases, the Progressive Student Union simply collected information from other organizations. Information about the Progressive Student Network is contained within this series. Arrangement is alphabetical.

arrangement.head: Organizations
arrangement.p: Organizations folders are arranged alphabetically by organization title.

scopecontent.head: Periodicals
scopecontent.p: The materials of this series include newspapers, newsletters, and magazines. The material dates from 1987 to 2002, but it is predominately from 1990 to 1996. The articles in these periodicals generally express progressive, liberal, or radical views. The periodicals were collected and kept by the Progressive Student Union. Periodicals are in alphabetical order by title. This series includes the GW Progressive Student Union publications Unfiltered and Buff and Blue.

arrangement.head: Periodicals
arrangement.p: The bulk of the periodicals folders are arranged alphabetically by periodical title. Within each folder, issues are arranged chronologically. Some periodicals are arranged in group folders at the end of the series.
